# React infinite loop — ref callback + useState pattern

## Symptom
Black screen at app mount. Console: `Maximum update depth exceeded. This can happen when a component repeatedly calls setState inside componentWillUpdate or componentDidUpdate.` React caps loop and renders error boundary (blank).

## Root cause
DaVinciStage.tsx wzór:
```tsx
const [slotRefs, setSlotRefs] = useState<SlotMap>({});
const registerSlot = useCallback((name, el) => {
  setSlotRefs(prev => prev[name] === el ? prev : { ...prev, [name]: el });
}, []);

// JSX:
<g ref={el => registerSlot('hero', el)} />
<g ref={el => registerSlot('manifesto', el)} />
//

## Problem

Po migracji v2→v3 (vanilla→Framer Motion) DaVinci overlay był całkowicie niewidoczny. CSS i Framer Motion animate={{ pathLength: 1 }} były poprawne. Build pass, TypeScript clean.

Przyczyna: `davinci.css` z v2 ma:
```css
.dv-hl-group { opacity: 0; transition: opacity 0.6s ease; }
.dv-hl-group.active { opacity: 1; }
```

W v2 JS dodaje klasę `.active` na odpowiednim scroll evencie. W v3 nie ma tego JS — Framer Motion animuje `pathLength` ale CSS `opacity: 0` blokuje całość zanim Framer cokolwiek zrobi.

Ten sam wzorzec: `[data-reveal]`, `data-anim`, `.exiting`, `.pin-content.active .element`.

## Solution

```css
/* Override runtime-activated CSS patterns for FM-driven v3 */
.dv-hl-group {
  opacity: 1 !important;  /* FM controls animation, not JS .active */
}
.dv-draw {
  stroke-dashoffset: 0 !important;
  transition: none !important;
}
```

Właściwe rozwiązanie długoterminowe: `swarm-source-analyzer` agent identyfikuje wszystkie `.active`-dependent CSS reguły w v2 i zwraca `runtime_patterns[]` z propozycją override lub FM replacement.

## Problem

Usunięcie ~70 inline `style="transition-delay: Xs; transition-duration: Ys; transition-timing-function: linear"` z SVG path elementów (DaVinci system) bez zepsucia animacji. JS (pin-scroll.js) override'uje te wartości przez `el.style.setProperty(...)`.

## Rozwiązanie

### 1. HTML: zamień inline style na data attributes

```html
<!-- PRZED -->
<path class="dv-draw" style="transition-delay: 0.5s; transition-duration: 2.0s; transition-timing-function: linear"/>

<!-- PO -->
<path class="dv-draw" data-delay="0.5" data-dur="2.0"/>
```

### 2. CSS (davinci.css): CSS vars w transition

```css
/* Zamiast transition: none — używaj CSS vars */
.dv-draw {
  stroke-dasharray: 1;
  stroke-dashoffset: 1;
  transition-property: stroke-dashoffset;
  transition-timing-function: linear;
  transition-duration: var(--dv-dur, 1s);
  transition-delay: var(--dv-delay, 0s);
}
```

**NIE używaj shorthand `transition:`** — pin-scroll.js override'uje longhands osobno przez setProperty.

### 3. JS: init CSS vars z data attrs

Dodaj do `main.js`:
```js
function initDvTransitions() {
  document.querySelectorAll('.dv-draw[data-delay], .dv-draw[data-dur]').forEach(el => {
    if (el.dataset.delay !== undefined) el.style.setProperty('--dv-delay', el.dataset.delay + 's');
    if (el.dataset.dur !== undefined) el.style.setProperty('--dv-dur', el.dataset.dur + 's');
  });
}
initDvTransitions(); // przed revealOnScroll()
```

### Dlaczego pin-scroll.js nadal działa

`el.style.setProperty('transition-duration', '0s')` = inline style = wyższy priorytet niż CSS class. Działa poprawnie. `el.style.transition = ''` czyści override, CSS var kopia in.

## Problem
Portfolio miało 3 rodzaje animation triggers, wszystkie timer-based:
1. `document.fonts.ready` → stroke-draw fires immediately (off-screen)
2. CSS `.active` class + `transition-delay: 2.1s` → timer odpala gdy section enters
3. `@keyframes` animation + `.frame-drawing` class → frame draws on threshold

User chciał Exat-style experience: każda animacja tied to scroll position. "Mogę zatrzymać animację w dowolnym miejscu."

## Solution — wzorzec: JS inline per RAF tick

W `pin-scroll.js` `tick()` funkcji (która odpala się każdy RAF dla każdej sticky sekcji):

```js
// prog = 0→1, scroll progress of pinned section
// Set ALL animated elements inline each frame:

var lineProg = Math.max(0, Math.min(1, prog / 0.35));
el.style.setProperty('stroke-dashoffset', (1 - lineProg).toFixed(3));
// stroke draws proportionally with scroll

var panelProg = Math.max(0, Math.min(1, (prog - 0.20) / 0.35));
panel.style.transform = 'translateY(' + (100 * (1 - panelProg)).toFixed(1) + '%)';
// panel slides up proportionally with scroll
```

Kluczowe zasady:
1. `el.style.setProperty()` dla SVG properties (nie camelCase — unreliable na SVG)
2. `el.style.transition = 'none'` (lub setProperty longhands) PRZED ustawieniem property
3. Gdy `isExiting = true`: wyczyść inline styles (pozwól CSS `.exiting` działać)
4. Dla pseudo-elementów: CSS custom property na parent
5. `transition: none` + CSS rules walczą → inline wins (patrz inne notes)

## Problem
W ramach scroll-scrub konwersji, JS ustawiał `el.style.transition = 'none'` na elementach CS01/CS02 żeby zapobiec CSS timer-based animations.

Przy wyjściu sekcji (`.exiting` class) elementy skakały o kilka pikseli zamiast płynnie wychodzić — exit jump bug.

## Solution
Gdy `isExiting = true`: wyczyść WSZYSTKIE inline styles — pozwól CSS `.exiting` rules przejąć kontrolę:

```js
if (isExiting) {
  var exitEls = ct.querySelectorAll(
    '.cs-card__metric-panel,.cs-card__content,.cs-card__strip--bottom,.proj__cta,.cs-card__metric'
  );
  exitEls.forEach(function(el) {
    el.style.transition = '';
    el.style.opacity = '';
    el.style.transform = '';
  });
}
```

Puste string (`''`) usuwa inline style property → CSS cascade decyduje (`.exiting` rules wygrywają).

## Problem
After scrolling past CS01 then back to manifesto, manifesto appeared "glued" to CS01 with content (Scale/System) missing. Section permanently shrunk. Pre-existing bug exposed by CS01 inline widget rebuild — old widget-overlay covered viewport during reverse transition, masking the missing manifesto state.

## Solution
**Remove the collapse mechanism entirely.** Manifesto state machine is fully reversible via the scrolled<400 / <800 / <1200 thresholds — text transform, stackBox clipPath, frame draw, exiting class all update synchronously per scroll position. Collapse was a perf optimization for one-way scroll that broke bidirectional scroll.

```js
// Removed:
// - if (ct.dataset.collapsed) return;  // line 162
// - The entire one-way collapse block (lines 220-239)
```

CSS `.manifesto--collapsed` rules kept but inert (class never set). Hero `dataset.collapsed` reference at line 100 left as dead code (never set anywhere).

## Rozwiązanie

Przed załadowaniem nowych patterns z Obsidian — usuń wszystkie stare obsidian entries:

```js
// Usuń stare obsidian entries, wstaw świeże
store = store.filter(e => !e.metadata?.fromObsidian);
for (const p of data.patterns) {
  store.push({ ...entry, metadata: { ...p.metadata, fromObsidian: true } });
}
fs.writeFileSync(storePath, JSON.stringify(store, null, 2));
```

## Efekt

66 entries → 16 entries. Wszystkie `fromObsidian: true`. Store spójny z vault'em.

## Problem

Nav text stuck light (cream-mode) when scrolling **backward** (up) out of cream section. White text invisible on dark section background.

Specific user report: scrolling wstecz przez cream sekcję → menu niewidoczne (białe na białym).

## Rozwiązanie

**Option A (recommended, simplest):** Section-specific classes.

- CS01 writes `html.cream-covers-nav-01` (not `cream-covers-nav`)
- CS03 writes `html.cream-covers-nav-03`
- `SiteNav` `MutationObserver` observes BOTH classes. `creamActive = classList.contains("cream-covers-nav-01") || classList.contains("cream-covers-nav-03")`
- Each section owns exclusive write to its own class → no race

```ts
// CS01 (after fix):
html.classList.toggle("cream-covers-nav-01", creamCoversNav);

// CS03 (after fix):
html.classList.toggle("cream-covers-nav-03", creamCoversNav);

// SiteNav MutationObserver callback:
const active =
  html.classList.contains("cream-covers-nav-01") ||
  html.classList.contains("cream-covers-nav-03");
setCreamActive(active);
```

MutationObserver config: `attributes: true, attributeFilter: ["class"]` (unchanged).

**Option B:** Custom event + Map-based aggregation (more decoupled but heavier).

