## Wzorzec

Helper hook that subscribes to a `MotionValue` and writes its value imperatively to a ref'd element's inline style. Bypasses motion v12 WAAPI scroll-timeline auto-promotion that mis-binds `style.opacity` (and other simple style props) to *document* scroll instead of a scoped `useScroll({ target })` source.

Returns a ref callback so the helper works for any element type without forwardRef gymnastics.

## Kod

```tsx
import { useEffect, useRef } from "react";
import { useMotionValueEvent, type MotionValue } from "motion/react";

function useInlineStyleFromMotionValue<E extends HTMLElement | SVGElement>(
  mv: MotionValue<number>,
  property: "opacity" | "transform",
  formatter?: (v: number) => string,
): (el: E | null) => void {
  const refEl = useRef<E | null>(null);

  const apply = (v: number): void => {
    const el = refEl.current;
    if (!el) return;
    const value = formatter ? formatter(v) : String(v);
    el.style.setProperty(property, value);
  };

  useMotionValueEvent(mv, "change", apply);

  useEffect(() => {
    // Initial paint covers the case where MotionValue already has a value
    // before the element mounts (scoped scroll progress != 0 on mount).
    apply(mv.get());
    // eslint-disable-next-line react-hooks/exhaustive-deps
  }, []);

  return (el) => {
    refEl.current = el;
    if (el) apply(mv.get());
  };
}
```

Usage with opacity:
```tsx
const stripOpacity = useTransform(progress, [0.55, 0.75], [0, 1], { clamp: true });
const stripRef = useInlineStyleFromMotionValue<HTMLDivElement>(stripOpacity, "opacity");
return <div ref={stripRef} className="..." />;
```

Usage with custom CSS var (formatter):
```tsx
const stripScale = useTransform(progress, [0.55, 0.75], [0, 1], { clamp: true });
const setStripScale = useInlineStyleFromMotionValue<HTMLDivElement>(
  stripScale,
  "transform",
  (v) => `scaleX(${v})`,
);
```

## Kiedy używać

- `useScroll({ target })` scoped progress feeding `style.opacity` on a `motion.div` — auto-promote misfires; use this helper to bypass
- Any animated CSS property where motion v12 auto-opt produces wrong values
- One-way write to DOM (no React state read of the value) — for state read use a normal `MotionValue` subscriber

NIE używaj for `y`/`x` transforms — motion 12.x transform promotion respects scoped scroll target; native `motion.div style={{ y }}` works correctly.

NIE używaj for cross-component reads — this is a write-side helper. If a downstream component needs the value, expose the MotionValue directly.

## Gotchas

- Initial apply via `useEffect(() => apply(mv.get()), [])` is mandatory — without it the element renders with no inline `opacity` until the first scroll tick, causing a flash of native CSS value (often 1 instead of 0).
- Ref callback (not `useRef`) so element identity changes are detected and the new node is painted immediately on mount.
- Subscribes per-element — for a list of 10 metrics use 10 hooks (or pre-compute 10 MotionValues and 10 refs). Don't try to fan out one hook over many refs.

