## Problem

CS01 scroll-driven opacity values diverged from inline computed opacity. Strip + CTA + bullet + title + metrics were bound via `motion.div style={{ opacity }}` where `opacity` came from `useTransform(progress, ...)` of a scoped `useScroll({ target })`. Visually elements never reached opacity 1 or stayed mostly invisible — values computed in React DOM panel matched expected, but rendered output did not.

Transform-style values (`y`, `transform`) on the same elements worked correctly. Only `opacity` broke.

## Kontekst

- `motion/react` 12.x in v3 (Vite + React 19). CS01 lives inside a `PinSection` with `useScrollProgress()` returning a scoped progress motion value (`useScroll({ target: stickyRef })`).
- Symptom appeared the moment a `MotionValue<number>` was assigned to `style.opacity` of a `motion.div`. Static `style.opacity` literals worked.
- Multiple elements affected once they used the scoped progress: strip, CTA, bullet, title, 3 metrics, 3 dots.

## Rozwiązanie

`motion/react` 12.x auto-promotes a `style.opacity` MotionValue binding into a native WAAPI scroll-timeline animation. The promotion picks `document` scroll as the timeline source instead of the scoped `useScroll({ target })`, so opacity is computed against the wrong scroll progress.

Workaround: bypass the optimization for any `useScroll({ target })`-derived MotionValue bound to opacity. Write the value imperatively through `useMotionValueEvent` into the element's inline style via a ref. Transform values stay on `motion.div` style binding (not affected).

Helper hook (see [[useInlineStyleFromMotionValue helper to bypass WAAPI auto-opt]]):

```tsx
function useInlineStyleFromMotionValue<E extends HTMLElement | SVGElement>(
  mv: MotionValue<number>,
  property: "opacity" | "transform",
  formatter?: (v: number) => string,
): (el: E | null) => void {
  const refEl = useRef<E | null>(null);
  const apply = (v: number) => {
    const el = refEl.current;
    if (!el) return;
    el.style.setProperty(property, formatter ? formatter(v) : String(v));
  };
  useMotionValueEvent(mv, "change", apply);
  useEffect(() => { apply(mv.get()); }, []);
  return (el) => { refEl.current = el; if (el) apply(mv.get()); };
}
```

Usage:
```tsx
const stripOpacity = useTransform(progress, [0.55, 0.75], [0, 1], { clamp: true });
const stripRef = useInlineStyleFromMotionValue<HTMLDivElement>(stripOpacity, "opacity");
return <div ref={stripRef}>...</div>;
```

## Dlaczego zadziałało

WAAPI scroll-timeline auto-opt requires a CSS-binding pipeline that the runtime can promote into native browser animation. Writing `el.style.opacity = "0.7"` directly via setProperty bypasses motion's MotionValue→CSS binding entirely — there is no MotionValue→style.opacity link to detect and promote. The value reaches the DOM through the same imperative path as a manual scroll handler, so the scoped progress source is preserved.

Transform values work via the standard `motion.div` style binding because motion 12.x promotes transforms differently (composited GPU pipeline, not WAAPI scroll-timeline) and the transform promotion does honor the scoped scroll target.

## Confirms

[[Framer Motion v12 CSS Scroll Timeline auto-opt — chrome-devtools blind spot]] — that note hypothesized 4 strategies. Strategy D ("useMotionValueEvent z manual update") is the one that works in this case. The chrome-devtools blind-spot framing in that note was disproved earlier (DaVinciStage portal bug), but the underlying WAAPI auto-promote pathology is real and confirmed here.

HYP-003 update candidate: motion v12 WAAPI auto-promote is a real bug, not a chrome-devtools artifact. Symptom is visible identically in chrome-devtools and user Chrome — the divergence appears between scoped useScroll target and document scroll, not between browsers.

